On my last night in “the colony” before journeying to Brazil, a rare thunderstorm strikes the Western Cape. The thunder applauds my departure as I fly across the Atlantic. I was blissfully unaware at the time, fidgeting in my window seat with excitement and discomfort, that the feeling of being indigenous is relative. A layover in Luanda gives me time to catch a glimpse of the full moon and transition from the Portuguese I grew up speaking in Maputo to a new accent — a new iteration. I land in São Paulo as dawn is breaking.
 
